message:
Thaipusam falls on 9th February 2017. It is a Hindu festival celebrated mostly by the Tamil community on the full moon in the Tamil month. A celebration of the triumph over evil and overcoming the evil teachings of greed, hatred and arrogance.

The festival signifies two important traditions:
- The birth of Lord Murugan (the youngest son of Lord Shiva and Pravati)
-  Parvati gave Lord Murugan a Vel "spear" so he could vanquish the evil demon

It is a public holiday in several states in Malaysia.

Happy Thaipusam to all our Hindu FBians :)

description:
Utterly Stunned · Exploring the hidden gem in Johor Bahru!

If you truly love nature, you would find beauty everywhere! Pretty sure that many of you are aware of this truly impressive place in JB that will make you leave your burden behind and totally immersed in the great scenery right in front of you. This place is none other than「Blue Lake Seri Alam」

You will be utterly stunned by this nature in your own city. Can you believe that it is an abandoned quarry site nestled within Seri Alam? It is located in Seri Alam, Plentong, Johor (facing University Kuala Lumpur Mitec). It is just an evidence how nature heals itself and yet still giving better view of mankinds. Even though the journey to reach there is rather challenging but you will for sure be amazed with this stunning view! Appreciate the beauty of nature around you while you can ❤

message:
Bukit Keteri, a well known karst limestone formation is located in the state of Perlis.
A spectacular limestone towers surrounded by endless rice paddies of Perlis can be quite a sight to behold. A short 20-minutes trek through the paddy fields to get to the foot of the hill is enough to give you a sense of zen-like elation. 
The climbs would then begin from inside of the cave follow along the arched openings looking out over the surrounding of countryside and the local mosque. The limestone facets of the climb is quite straightforward and the climber should probably take few hours to reach “Belly Button Window” which is the scenic view of Bukit Keteri.

#perlis #bukitketeri #tmsingapore

message:
Did you know that you can scuba dive in Kelantan?

The first boat that was sunk in the Pacific Naval hostilities of WW2 called 'Awagisan Maru' and it was a 9,794 gross ton freighter that now lies in 20 metres (66 ft) of water off the coast of Pantai Sabak in Kota Bharu. It is fast becoming a popular diving destination due to its remarkable history.

It is home to schooling fish, giant barracudas and an abundance of pelagic life that is a magnet for diving enthusiasts. 

A 30 minute boat trip from Kota Bharu to the dive site is highly sought after by interested scuba divers and war buffs alike.

#tmsingapore #scubadivinginkelantan

message:
Have you visited Kampung Bharu in Kuala Lumpur?

Kampung Bharu is one of the oldest Malay settlements in the capital city. There are guided walking tour led by qualified guides with in-depth knowledge of Kampung Bharu history.

During the two-and-a-half-hour guided walk, tourists will also have the opportunity try out popular dishes and food venues that offers traditional delicacies such as bubor lambok, kuih-muih and the famous Nasi Lemak Antarabangsa at the Malay Food Street.

The guided walk is free for all and is conducted every Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday from 4.30pm to 7pm.

Information:
1. Trail One - Kuala Lumpur Heritage Trail meeting point is at the Kuala Lumpur City Gallery, Dataran Merdeka, conducted every Monday, Wednesday & Saturday from 9am to 11.30am.

2. Trail Two - Old KL & Nature Walk meeting point is at Kuala Lumpur Tourism Bureau, Jalan Tangsi, conducted every Tuesday & Thursday from 9am to 11.30am.

3. Trail Four - Kuala Lumpur Night Walk meeting point is at Arch Cafe at the Old Market Square. The tour is available on Saturday from 6.30pm to 9pm.

More Details: http://bit.ly/2bwdT5d

data.message:
I've done this trip a number of times in both directions and this is hands down the most efficient and comfortable way to cross the causeway, just make sure to book your tickets in advance for peak times. You go through a separate customs so you don't get caught in the human jam and the train isn't subject to traffic jams, even during peak times on public holidays the whole process form JB Sentral to Woodlands CIQ or reverse takes about 20 minutes including immigration.

I've been stuck in 4 hour jams at immigration before and traffic jams so bad decided to ditch the bus and walk the causeway. The KTM train is the best option.

Here's the link to book online with KTMB

https://intranet.ktmb.com.my/e-ticket/login.aspx
5 minutes is maximum allowed time, actual journey time is about 3 minutes.
Nice

message:
If you are an active social media user and is willing to go the extra mile for a beautiful shot, may we introduce the almost best kept secret, only known to the nearby villagers. 

Located in the Straits of Malacca, this 'secret island' shows itself only twice a month: During the new moon and full moon. 
The unnamed island is accessible by a 30-minute boat ride from the fishing village of Jeram, Selangor. Besides picture-perfect scenery, the island is also home to a multitude of marine organisms. 

Location: Sasaran, Kuala Selangor (a.k.a Sky Mirror)

#instagramworthy #tmsingapore #skymirrorkualaselangor

In cooperation with Tourism Malaysia The Travel Malaysia fair held biannually provides an excellent opportunity for Singapore residents and foreign visitors alike to select from a unique mélange of attractions and holiday destinations as well as a multitude of special products from various states of Malaysia.

More information about our packages can be found here at https://www.wtstravel.com.sg/index.php/tours/malaysia 

The upcoming Travel Malaysia Fair will be held from 14 – 16 October at Singapore Expo Hall 6B.

description:
Covered the event where Madam Noor Aine Ismail will step down and return to Malaysia. Mr Ishak will take over her. 

Never have I seen so much outpouring of love and respect from staff. Such bosses are hard to come by where the balancing act of getting things done, to motivate and without hurting feelings is not an easy one and is considered an art and not science.

I don't know her for long but during my short conversations with her, I can sense her sincerity through and through. I wish her the best in her future endeavours.
message:
The time to bid farewell to our Director, Mdm Noor Aine & to welcome our new Director, Mr Ishak Ismail.

A big Thank You to all our friends from the Media, Travel Trade & Partners who came together to make this event a success.

Photography Credit: Wilson Wong

message:
Dark Cave is one of the main caves at Batu Caves hill, located 15km away from the Kuala Lumpur city centre.

It is among the most researched tropical caves in the world, and a number of scientists and researchers have conducted major research in the cave.

It is one of the must-see Batu Caves attractions for travellers.

message:
Nasi dagang.

This is one dish, we believed, can't be found in Singapore (home-cooked meal not counted)  :P

A Malaysian and Southern Thai dish consisting of rice steamed in coconut milk, fish curry and extra ingredients such as fried shaved coconut, hard-boiled eggs and vegetable pickles, Nasi Dagang literally means "Trading Rice". 
It is a well-known breakfast food in the states on the East Coast of Peninsular Malaysia, such as Terengganu and Kelantan.

Check out this video.  :)

message:
Hungry Ghost Festival (3 - 31 August)

Chinese communities in Malaysia believe that the gates of Hell open on the 7th lunar month, freeing the spirits of the dead to roam in the world of the living. According to custom, these ghosts can get up to mischief if ignored so all sorts of offerings are made during this period.

Song stages known as getai are set up, Chinese opera and puppet shows held for both the living and the dead. More modern entertainments like karaoke and dance contests are also held on these stages, presumably for the spirits of the more recently deceased.

What are some of the DO's and DON'Ts during the Hungry Ghost Month that you remember most?

#sharing #hungryghostmonthinmalaysia

message:
What's for Breakfast on this Wet Thursday Morning?

Known as Mee Kari/咖喱麵/Curry Mee, this noodle dish is unique to Malaysia, usually made up of thin yellow egg noodles or/and string thin mee-hoon (rice vermicelli) with spicy curry soup, chilli/sambal, coconut milk, and a choice of dried tofu, prawns, cuttlefish,chicken, egg and mint leaves. 

In southern part of  Malaysia, it is called Laksa Kari/咖喱喇沙/Curry Laksa when cockles are used.

Image by: https://drnaz.wordpress.com/

description:
万众期待的空中花园之小小童话世界将在6月7号正式掀幕啦！

你们将会见证到地球非常历史性的一刻！
童话故事里的卡通人物穿越时空入侵峇株巴辖，并且侵霸了老街坊第二座空中花园，在那里筑建自己的糖果屋，水果屋 和 雪糕屋。
就连白雪公主和七个小矮人也把小木屋搬迁至此，灰姑娘的南瓜车更是快马加鞭赶在7号前抵达老街坊。

它们势必为地球的民众带来前所未有的感官体验与欢乐！
快带上一家大小前来探索童话世界的神奇！必定让你惊喜万分！

Come along with your family to discover the mysteries in this new fairyland and you will not be disappointed!

data.message:
Langkawi would be my ideal destination as it has the luxury resorts that my wife love. We can spend romantic evening by the beach. 

This will be the first year my wife is celebrating Mother's Day as she had given birth to a lovely son last October. Hope to give my son & wife a special treat away from Singapore.

My ideal holiday is to Langkawi n looking forward to visit this place. It's full of historical places (lagenda) to visit and  to relax at the beach with your loved ones. Secondly , cameron Highlands as of the greenery and cooling environment. 
Both places are in my visiting list of plces to go n relax

The ideal holiday destination in Malaysia will be Langkawi. Clean and Beautiful Beaches, Shopping Paradise,Awesome Tradisional Foods,Visit to Historicals,Enjoying Kampong stay,Green Padi Field and Colorful Culturals and Scenery

Johor Bahru is your ideal holiday destination. Hope i could win this staycation to surprice my mom during this mother's day. My mother deserves to win this Super prize becuase she is the BEST mom in the workd and appreciate good food. She's an incredible kind, loving and caring person, who every changes people's live with her warm heart and caring nature. She is the type of person you always want to be around and when leaving her company you with good treats always feel happier. She is my living Guardian Angel.

: it have to be Kuala Lumpur... As it's the shopping haven for me & mummy... Easy to find muslimah clothing .. And of course, easy to find Halal Food... All in all, it's the best place to go & we wont get bored of it.. 

You should select me as the winner cos it's been a loong loong time since i go on a holiday shopping spree with my mom.. And we badly need a getaway cos we are kind of tired from travelling to n fro from the hospital... So this kind of distraction will be good...

My favourite is JB simply cos i stay in NW of Singapore and it is so convenient to go there for shopping and entertainment all the time! Love the street food, the variety of fashion and fun activities to do there! A staycation would be awesome cos there's too much to shop and play! Can imagine a weekend of ktv, buffet and shopping with mum! <3

Have always promoted JB to all my friends and brought many friends there to try the famous food so I could definitely help share more awesome stuff about JB! <3

My ideal holiday destination in Malaysia is Rawa Island... I have my wedding photos taken there and from then on, I simply fall in love with this beautiful island of blue sky and clear sea water!

Hope to win this staycation and have an enjoyable trip with my mum. It's been so long since we went for a trip together and let her have a rest and relax moment.

#tmsingapore #mothersdaycontest

1. My ideal holiday would be Kuching. The whole family being cat lovers, we're fascinated by all things cats, would love to visit the cat museum and possibly a cat cafe (if they have one, do they?)if I had a chance..Kuching just has its appeal..
2. Why should I win? Because my mum's birthday and Mothers' Day are real close, just afew days apart, would love to give her a little surprise..

My ideal holiday destination is  Cameron Highlands as we love to see mountains and great heights.. I should be selected as a winner because want to take kids on a holiday as their dad is usually busy in work, It will be a great bonding and outing for Mom and kids on this Mother's day!

1. Penang would be my ideal holiday destination in Malaysia, for the excellent food, beautiful beaches, picturesque scenery and wonderful and friendly penangites!
2. Hope to win this and bring my mum for this hotel stay and to bring her to eat, shop and relax and make her a very happy lady and for a memorable Mother's Day surprise.

1. Malacca has and always will be my ideal holiday destination. A UNESCO world heritage site, it offers beautiful historical monuments, great food and fabulous shopping!
2. Hope to be the lucky winner and celebrate a wonderful and joyous staycation with my loved ones!

I love the Cameron Highlands to visit the hills and trek down the trails destination and to take a much needed break from the tropical climate.

I would love to win this for my mum because I want to pamper and thank her for taking such great care of me and my family! My mum gave up the most important things in her life so that I could take on the most important things in mine. Mom, thanks for all the sacrifices you have made. Best friends come and go, boyfriends and girlfriends love and move on, bosses hire and fire but the only person present through it all is a mother. Thanks for always being there for me. Whenever I am in trouble I ask my heart ‘What should I do?’ Every single time it replies ‘Do what your mother would tell you to’. Mom, thanks for being my guiding light.Thanks for everything mom!

My ideal holiday destination will be tioman. I love it because the water there is very clean and it is the nearest diving spot to singapore. 
Furthermore Tioman have much to offer to me. Although it is a mini version of bali but I still fine worth to go. Tioman have a lesser tourist which I love it. I can experience communicate with the locals and understand their culture.
I hope that I will win it ❤

My ideal holiday destination is Penang! This is where my mum and dad had their honeymoon 25 years ago. Penang is a place where the East meets the West. A place which is unique by all means, colonial architecture, peranakan food, lush green forest, soft sandy beach, amazing wildlife. Simply beautiful!

This month is my mum and dad 25th wedding anniversary. My mum is the breath of my soul and the light of my heart, the rock that stood strong in face of any storms clouds in the horizon. She is the most magical person in my life. Hope to win a lovely stay for them together!

My ideal holiday is at Pulau Besar, as island in Mersing. It is secluded and exclusive and not many people knows about it. Pulau Besar is a combination of nature and relaxation. I stayed with the locals as the main resort (Aseania Beach Resort) was not yet ready. The locals took me to snorkle, visit the durian trees near the top of the mountain, fishing and more. If you are keen on nature and a simple place to relax, Pulau Besar is the place to be. A nice dinner with nature would be great to celebrate Mother's Day.

1)My ideal Holiday in Malaysia is Kuala Lumpur,we can eat and shop whole day that is me with my kids and family favourite pasttime.
2)Hope to win this to surprise my mum and family,we can go eat and shop and made my mum very happy.Also we can recommend friends and family this hotel at Jb we never stay before as we love staycation at Johor bahru also with many food and shopping options.

1. Johor Bahru is my ideal holiday destination because it is so convenient for a weekend getaway with lots of shopping and great eats! 😍

2. Please select me as the winner so that I can give mum a wonderful surprise and whisk her away for a short holiday at Thistle Johor Bahru where we can relax and bond over great food and shopping! 😊

#tmsingapore #mothersdaycontest

Johor Bahru is my ideal holiday destination with my mum because we've yet to explore the wonders of this awesome city just a stone's throw away from Singapore :)

I hope to be selected as the winner to surprise my mum. 
My father was hospitalised a couple of months ago. My mum took leave from work and took great care of my father, preparing meals for him and accompanying him at the hospital. Now that my father is recuperating well and that Mother's Day is around the corner, what better way to thank my mum for ever being so sacrificial and to celebrate than to bring my mum on a short getaway? She is bound to be delighted! Hope to win. Thank you :))

1. Penang in Malaysia is my ideal holiday destination for the delicious foods.
2. Please select me as the winner so that I can take that special woman in my life a  great holiday to show my appreciation.

Liked and shared.

#tmsingapore #mothersdaycontest

Su Chin
Christy Lee

My ideal holiday destination in Malaysia is Langkawi - fringed with long, white beaches and with an interior of jungle covered hills and craggy mountain peaks, it's an amazing beautiful beach location! 

Pls choose me as the winner because I want to reward my mum with a staycation! I know she will love this staycation at the Luxury Thistle hotel! I want to win this staycation for my supermom because I want to reward my supermom who 

[S]acrificed herself building up a beautiful family with love for us so I can call it a home.

[U]nderstands me and can advise and guide me to stand up and take a step at a time in the toughest times in my life

[P]roviding for the family and always putting the family first because she loves us so much

[E]ternally guiding me in the right direction while showing and giving support, encouragement and inspiration in whatever I do,

[R]adiant and beautiful inside and outside !!

#tmsingapore #mothersdaycontest

caption:
Diving:

Miri is a popular dive destination due to an abundance of pristine patch reefs. The Miri-Sibuti Coral Reefs National Park, lying at depths ranging from 7 to 30 metres has an average visibility of 10 to 30 metres. There are also some interesting wreck dives. The nearest dive site is a mere ten minutes from the marina bay jetty. One can land in Miri and be in water two hours later. Local dive operators offer certification programme as well.  Water temperature at the start of the season is normally 26 to 27ºC but can be as low as 23ºC at depth, as the NE monsoon still brings in cold water from the northern Pacific. By May the water temperature reaches the more normal 29 to 30ºC.  The best time to dive is from late March through November each year.  The diversity and accessibility of corals and other marine life on the reefs is amongst the best in the region.

Photos by Mr. Clement Lee, Tourism Advisor of Malaysia (Industry pioneer, icon and distinguished PADI Course Director)

The Datun Julud or hornbill dance is a traditional women's dance that is popular among the Kenyah tribe. This dance was said to have been created by a Kenyah prince called Nyik Selung, to symbolise happiness and gratitude.
Today, the Datun Julud has become a dance of formal entertainment that is often performed in the rumah panjang (longhouse) to greet visitors and tourists.

Question: Name the State that this traditional dance originate from?

description:
Our commitment to quality and excellence paid off in a big way in 2015, with the company scoring a slew of award wins. These included the Enterprise 50 Award, the Singapore Prestige Brand Award and the Best Visual Merchandising Award at the Singapore Heartland Enterprise Award 2015 ceremony.

And to top it off, we were also named Best Foreign Tour Operator at the Malaysia Tourism Awards yesterday. The prestigious Malaysia Tourism Award (MTA) was introduced in 1987 by the then Ministry of Arts, Culture and Tourism (now known as Ministry of Tourism And Culture Malaysia) to increase the standards of professionalism and service delivery of the tourism industry in Malaysia. This year is the 19th edition of the MTA since its debut.
message:
CONGRATULATIONS to our partner, WTS Travel & Tours Pte Ltd for winning the Best Foreign Tour Operator (ASEAN). :)

description:
Sekinchan is a small, cozy farming and fishing village just north of Kuala Lumpur. It has gotten extremely popular over the years with city slickers heading over to enjoy the simpler things in life.

The drive to Sekinchan is scenic with oil palm trees along the coastal road, stalls selling handmade cotton pillows, eateries offering a wide variety of local delicacies and almost in the middle of nowhere, vast expanses of paddy fields bordering a stretch of fishing villages.

The picturesque landscape in Sekinchan especially when the sun sets against the vast padi fields and stretch of fishing villages is the one of the many reasons why visitors call this town 'a photographer’s haven'.

A MUST-VISIT for photographers.  :)

GPS Location : N03 30.984 E101 06.891

description:
Love it or hate it, the fruits season is back!

Everyone knows that the fruits season has arrived. We've seen a lot of stalls selling all kinds of fruits but the number one favorite goes to our very own King of Fruits - the Durian! 

How to choose a durian? I normally sniff along the seams of split lines.  You gotta know the drill, if there is no aroma, then it is unripe and if the aroma is too strong, it's probably over-ripe.  Tell us how do you normally choose your Durian?

Championing cross cultural experience, visitors to the Mitsui Outlet Park KLIA Sepang, locals and foreigners alike can also experience a flavour of Japanese culture and lifestyle through ‘Japan Avenue’, a Japanese Specialty Store offering authentic Japanese gifts, souvenirs, snacks, and culinary delights. Presently, ‘Japan Avenue’ is hosting the Food Kingdom Miyagi Gourmet Fair, which is until 6th December 2015. 

Visitors will be able to purchase fresh seafood imported from Miyagi as well as packed specialty delights such as Milky Oyster Sauce. During this promotion, Japanese restaurants within Japan Avenue namely Sushi Maru and Fan Japan will also introduce speciality dishes from Miyagi.

description:
Good Morning FBians, have you had breakfast yet?
May we introduce the up & coming hit dish in Malaysia. Known as Roti Canai Special, while some locals called it Roti Banjir Special, this dish is prata soaked in curry with a little special ingredient: 3 minutes Soft Boiled Eggs! 
While we do admit that the presentation does not look appetising, it certainly taste heavenly. (Do not judge a book by its cover)  ^_^
P/S: we recommend pepper with light soya sauce and sambal. It goes well with this dish. 

#vmy2014 #tmsingapore

caption: Sg Lembing Road Trip - 3rd to 4th October 2015
description:
Sg Lembing Road Trip  (3rd to 4th October 2015)
Venue: Sungai Lembing		
Hotel: Pollock View Resort

Date of departure: 3rd October, returning on the 4th October 2015 

Briefing session: 22nd Sept 2015, 7pm.

Payment: Cash or cheque at briefing session		 

Walkie-Talkie			
Rental at $10 per set per day (Deposit is $50 – returnable)

Mode of travel: Convoy  

Tour price		
Twin/triple sharing	$158 per person
Child without bed	$68 per child aged between 3 and 12 yrs
Child with bed		$99 per child aged between 3 and 12 years

Insurance is not included

Optional Tour		
Rainbow Fall with lunch (highly recommended)
(RM80 per person – pay at Tour Counter)

General information
Our itinerary is designed in such a way that all participants are able to feel the total freedom of a driving holiday and yet having the added advantage of an escorted group self drive holiday. The itinerary is not too intrusive for those who prefer to do their own things while on tour. For those who would like to do things in a group, this is a dream come true with safety in numbers. 

Itinerary

3rd October 2015 (Sat)	 Singapore to Sg Lembing (Lunch and dinner included) 
0530	Registration 

Breakfast at Kiang Kee Bak Kut Tay  
Drive up to Kuantan
Lunch included 
1400 	Convoy continues to Sg Lembing
1500 	Check in at Pollock View Resort, Pollock Creek
1800	Visit noodle factory and roast pork/char siew factory 
1900	BBQ dinner included

4th October 2015 (Sun) Sg Lembing Day Tour 
Free & Easy Morning:

Explore Sg Lembing town. Sg Lembing sleeps from Mondays to Fridays. This sleepy hamlet only wakes on the weekend. Everyone, both locals and tourists will meet on a Sunday morning at the market to socialize. This is something to look out for while here.
It is a highlight for both locals and tourists alike.
Don’t miss Sg Lembing Starbuck coffee!
Or go visit Sg Lembing Tin Mines (RM30 per person – pay at the entry gate)   

OR sign up for morning tour to Rainbow Fall with lunch (highly recommended) 
(RM80 per person)

0600 	Wake- up call & breakfast
0615	Set off for Sungai Lembing Morning Day Tour
1300	Lunch at Sungei Lembing included (includes the famous roast pork/char siew from Sg Lembing. The popular tomato noodles is also included)  
1400	Check out of hotel and we are on our way home.

En-route, we stop to stock up some local Rompin pineapples for our love ones at home.
We should be home into Singapore about dinner time.

We kiss and hug Good Bye…    

End of tour.

Note:
You have the option to extend your stay at Sg Lembing or Kuantan.
Please advise. Pay extension at hotel direct. 

Chris Ng
HP 91814298
Fax 68540071
FootWorks Media Pte Ltd

message:
Did you hear?

11-year-old superclub Zouk Kuala Lumpur (Zouk KL) has moved to its new home at TREC Malaysia's first purpose-built urban lifestyle, entertainment destination and Kuala Lumpur's largest F&B enclave located along the bustling downtown Jalan Tun Razak.

With a built-up space of 60,000 sq ft, the new RM38 million (S$14.8m) nightspot is the most expensive club ever built in Malaysia, and it will be the beacon of KL's entertainment. The new Zouk KL comprises several venues including a VIP bar lounge; a member's lounge; a café and a rooftop deck overlooking the expansive views of the Royal Selangor Golf Club. Zouk KL will also offer a dedicated VIP concierge service.

Zouk KL is the only nightspot in the metropolis that has a 5am operating license.

message:
"When is turtle hatching season?"

We get this question alot. So we decided to share. 
It's between May and August. (Peak egg laying months are June and July).

Recommended Places to Visit:
• Rantau Abang Beach. Terengganu
• Tanjung Jara Beach, Terengganu
• Similajau National Park, Bintulu Sarawak
• Turtle Bay, Pangkor Island Perak

Four types of marine turtles – the Leatherback, Green, Hawksbill, and Olive Ridley turtles have chosen Malaysia to lay their eggs. To be able to watch them laying eggs is truly a fascinating experience.

message:
Introducing, 2015 Malaysia International Mask Festival.

The Malaysia International Mask Festival will be held on the 14, 15 and 16 August 2015 at Esplanade KLCC Park, Kuala Lumpur from 9am to 11pm respectively. It is an event that highlights the uniqueness of masks as prop performances in various cultural arts of the country. 

The festival will see the involvement of all major races in Malaysia including indigenous people and the Sabah and Sarawak society,culminating in the venue to preserve and share the artisanal concepts and significance of masks in their performances and escapades.

message:
Lemang can be found throughout Malaysia and is especially popular among the Malay community besides the Iban and other natives.

Normally, Lemang is usually eaten with Rendang (Spicy Chicken Curry) and Serunding (Meat Floss). Lemang can be seen sold on road sides and street food centres during the festive season of Hari Raya.

A traditional food made from glutinous rice, coconut milk and salt, cooked in a hollowed bamboo stick lined with banana leaves in order to prevent the rice from sticking to the bamboo.

description:
SAYANG KINABALU  - WE LOVE MT. KINABALU  VIDEO
An ode to the spiritual value and beauty that runs forever deep in the memories of those who have scaled the majestic Mount Kinabalu, a song that tells the story of a bond between Man and Mountain that will never be broken. Through thick and thin, rain or shine, Sayang Kinabalu.

Please Watch, Share & Like 
Click here for YouTube link - https://youtu.be/bL4TUfmRh_Q  
-------------------------------------------------------
This music video is dedicated by the Amazing Borneo team to our beloved Mount Kinabalu in the aftermath of 5 June 2015’s earthquake.  Through this MV, we wish to remember our heroic local mountain guides who sacrificed their lives on that fateful day and to recognize the bravery and spirit of many others who volunteered their help in the rescue efforts.  

Despite the changes that the earthquake left on her mountain face and trail, Mount Kinabalu will forever remain the pride and glory of Sabah and Malaysia.

-------------------------------------------------------

Original Singer : Asmin Mudin (Sabahan)

description:
It is with a heavy heart to announce that we have lost another one of our mountain guides, Joseph Selungin, age 33, in the wake of Sabah Earthquake that jolted Mt.Kinabalu.

The earthquake that rocked the mountain on the 5th of June, 7:15am triggered landslides along with rocks and boulders that tumbled down, destroying trails and sadly, taking lives. Joseph was found beneath a boulder, in the heroic act of shielding two of his guests. Unfortunately, the three of them didn’t survive.

Joseph was last seen hugging two of his guests, in an attempt to protect them, using his body as a shield, an account related by his fellow mountain guide colleague, Sharulnizam Suhaji. Sharulnizam describes Joseph as an easy-going person with a good heart, soft-spoken and always kind. 

Joseph has been a member of our team for almost 2 months. He has brought nothing but good memories and experiences for our fellow climbers. A man of courage and uncompromising thoughtfulness. His good-will and high-spirits will forever be remembered by all the lives he has touched.

Joseph left behind a loving wife, a 4-year old son and a 2-year old daughter. He promised his wife that he will come back to celebrate their wedding anniversary on the 12th of June. Our heartfelt condolences goes out to his family and to those affected. 
We will miss you Joseph, you live on in the love you gave, and the laughter you shared, in our thoughts and in our memories, forever.

Having breakfast?

Wouldn't most of you like to have plain flat sheet-type of chee cheong fun that are extra smooth and tender? 
Locals in Ipoh believed it has got something to do with the water flowing from the limestone caves that surround this tin-mining town.

The Ipoh style of eating chee cheong fun is by ladling over some shallot oil and soy sauce, followed by a sprinkle of fried shallots and sesame over it, with pickled green chillies on the side.

Simply Yummy... :)

description:
Swee Kang 

Swee Kang, a famous dessert shop in Kuching, Sarawak, has been a favourite among the locals for more than 50 years. The varied range of desserts available at this shop is massive as they practice the policy of always delivering what customers request, even if it involves inventing a new kind of dessert. If it’s really good, your “invention” might even be a permanent option on the menu! A must try at Swee Kang? Their jagung susu!

Try them out here : Lot 176 Jalan Haji Taha, 93400, Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia.

message:
Attention all Foodie Explorers out there, we would like to recommend this breakfast place located in Yong Peng, Ayer Hitam, Johor.
Locally known for their Nasi Arab Dulang (Nasi Arab, served in a tray), this roadside restaurant may have a simple ambience but is always filled with patrons the moment it opens for business (especially so on weekends and holidays).

The Nasi Arab Dulang cost RM 45 and it serves for about 5 people. 
If Nasi Arab isn't your thing, Mee Rebus is equally popular.

Tip: Be there early to avoid dissappointment.

Restaurant: Kari Kambing 40 Hari
Address: 215 Kg. Hj. Ghaffar, Bt 5 1/2, Yong Peng 83730
Operation Hours: 7am - 12 noon
Phone: 019-6272243

Tourists who shopped in Malaysia during their stay will be able to claim the amount spent on Goods and Services Tax (GST) over items bought through the Tourism Refund Scheme (TRS) counters at eight main airports from today. 

Tourists are reminded to obtain the tax-free form upon payment, before claiming the refund.
At the airport, take the purchased items, receipts and passport to the customs desk to get the tax free form validated. Then, take the validated tax free form, passport and credit card (if any) to the counter for redemption.

NOTE:
The refund is not applicable to those who travelled by land or sea.

message:
Nasi ambeng or Nasi ambang is a fragrant rice dish consists of white rice prepared with chicken curry or chicken cooked in soy sauce, vegetables, fried noodles, some salted fish, fried coconut flesh, and so on. It is cooked during important celebrations and served in a tray to be shared by four to five people.  

Come and experience the unique, communal dining style and delicious food of the Javanese-Malay people at the Nasi Ambang Carnival on 17 & 18 April at  Homestay Banghuris, Sg. Pelek, Sepang Selangor.

For places to eat Nasi ambang in Johor, see http://johorkaki.blogspot.sg/

Good Morning FBians, have you had breakfast yet?
May we introduce the up & coming hit dish in Malaysia. Known as Roti Canai Special, while some locals called it Roti Banjir Special, this dish is prata soaked in curry with a little special ingredient: 3 minutes Soft Boiled Eggs! 
While we do admit that the presentation does not look appetising, it certainly taste heavenly. (Do not judge a book by its cover)  ^_^
P/S: we recommend pepper with light soya sauce and sambal. It goes well with this dish.

description: Check out the new video teaser of Melaka Alive show.
message:
Keen to experience this new attraction in Melaka? We have 3 pairs of tickets to giveaway.  :)
Simply tell us why you deserve to win a pair of tickets.


Bringing to life 6 centuries of history, Melaka Alive is a ticketed experience among the existing heritage buildings and museums. Attractions include special effects theatres and historical shows as well as Malaysian arts and crafts.

Set on board a ship inspired stage, the tale of Panglima Awang is brought to life in a play, centred on his life and the invasion of the Portuguese. Combining carefully studied historical facts, live theatre, and the traditional Malay dance with theme park know-how, the play will show the importance of Melaka in Asian trade as well as the invasion of the city.

The attractions are to be framed by a night festival outside serving as a marketplace fashioned after the grounds of the 15th century Sultan’s Palace. The site will function as a central hub with retail, food and beverages served from traditional Malay ox carts with theatrical performances in the background adding to the atmosphere bringing to life moments from history.

#tmsingapore #myfest2015 #yof2015

If you're feeling extra adventurous, you can experience the thrilling view from the Hanging Bridge as well!

description: This is one of Fusion Shadow Play project called: Peperangan Bintang, www.facebook.com/peperanganbintang Main objective for this project is to re-promote thi...
message:
Shadow Puppets (also known as Wayang Kulit) presents stories of mythical & morality tales. The puppets are made primarily of leather and manipulated with sticks or buffalo horn handles. Shadows are cast using an oil lamp or, in modern times, a halogen light, onto a cotton cloth background. They are often associated with gamelan music.

In a twist to re-promote this traditional Malaysia culture to the younger generation, Fusion Wayang Kulit was introduced, by combining it with modern Sci-Fi such as Star Wars.

Catch Fusion Wayang Kulit today and tomorrow for a unique performance.
Date: 31 Oct & 1 Nov 2014
Venue: Malay Heritage Centre
Time: 8.30pm to 10.30pm (Free Admission)
name: PBWK (Peperangan Bintang Wayang Kulit) preview- 18th Oct 2013

Happening on 28 – 30 November 2014 at the Whiteaways Arcade, indulge in panel discussions, workshops, film screenings and more with your favorite international and local authors. Experience intriguing panel discussions topics such as self-censorship and the art of political biography amongst others.

What’s more, you can expect to see big names like Kassim Ahmad in conversation with Ahmad Fuad Rahmat, Susan Barker in conversation with Bernice Chauly, and enjoy a literary lunch with award-winning Miguel Syjuco.

So head down to facebook.com/georgetownlitfest to find out more about this festival, or book your tickets at www.georgetownlitfest.com

message:
Deepavali (Diwali) is known as the Festival of Lights, symbolizing the triumph of good over evil and is celebrated by those of Hindu faith.

The celebration is incomplete without a wide assortment of goodies. These are the 9 MUST-TRY sweet treats during this glorious festive season in Malaysia. 

Where to go in Kuala Lumpur during Deepavali?

There are two areas where you can witness the Deepavali preparations and celebrations. Both are known as Little India. 

One is located in the area called Brickfields, which lies within walking distance of KL Sentral (the main central train station of KL). Just follow the signs to the Monorail KL station. 

The other area is located along Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman, easy to reach from RapidKL metro station Masjid Jamek, or Monorail station Medan Tuanku.

Terengganu has a Peranakan community as well.They may not be as popular as their Penang and Malacca counterparts but Terengganu also has a rich Peranakan heritage with its own distinct qualities.

Example: In Penang and Malacca, the men and women are referred to as Baba and Nyonya but in Terengganu, they are called Mek and Awang.

caption:
Taman Negara (National Park) is the first and the oldest official Protected Area in the country. The most popular activities at Taman Negara are river cruises and jungle trekking. The canopy walk is also a must-see, offering a fantastic close up view of activity in the rainforest canopy.
Observation hides are another great way to observe wildlife. Simple huts built high above the ground allow guests to stay overnight to catch opportunities to observe animals in their natural habitat. Cave exploration is also available, either by boat or by foot.

caption:
Taman Negara (National Park) is the first and the oldest official Protected Area in the country. The most popular activities at Taman Negara are river cruises and jungle trekking. The canopy walk is also a must-see, offering a fantastic close up view of activity in the rainforest canopy.
Observation hides are another great way to observe wildlife. Simple huts built high above the ground allow guests to stay overnight to catch opportunities to observe animals in their natural habitat. Cave exploration is also available, either by boat or by foot.

message:
George Town Festival is a month-long festival that has turned into a proudly Penang arts institution. From its start as a series of arts and culture events in celebration of George Town’s listing as a UNESCO Heritage Site in 2008, George Town Festival was mooted and celebrated its first inauguration in 2010.

Taking place the entire month of August 2014, a dazzling array of international and local performances, exhibitions, and creative events that celebrates the arts and positions Penang as one of the ASEAN region’s major cultural hotspots.

For the complete schedule please visit http://georgetownfestival.com/programmes/ 

#georgetown #penang #malaysia #festival #malaysiatrulyasia #tmsingapore

Therefore the level of standard is beyond expectation. However when I read the feedback from the Internet on Citrus Hotel, Johore Bharu, I gave myself a trial. Consequently I booked my reservation. message: How was your 2nd day of Hari Raya Aidilfitri celebration? On our way back to Singapore from Kuala Selangor, we took a detour and headed to Rembau in Negeri Sembilan. Rembau is one of the earliest Minang settlements in the Peninsular Malaysia, thus some of the houses we saw along the way shows an influence of Minang architecture. Upon our arrival in Rembau, we visited the kampung residence of Malaysia's Celebrity Chef, Dato' Chef Ismail Ahmad's (owner of Restoran Rebung Dato' Chef Ismail) and joined in his Hari Raya celebration. Thank you, Dato' Chef Ismail for hosting us.

message:
When visiting the state of Perlis, look out for this refreshing drink called Air Nira.

"Air Nira" is taken from the Malay language which means fresh juice obtained from the blossom of palm tree. 

The tasty sap of fresh palm is a product of different species made solely by natural forces.

If fermented, this juice will turn alcoholic with time. 

Air Nira can be bought at most roadside stalls and restaurants in Perlis.

#airnira #perlis #Malaysia #refreshingdrink

message:
Sabah now has the world’s longest zip line – the bigger-scale version of the flying fox that enables users to traverse from the top to the bottom of a cable attached to a moving pulley – that will give the thrill of literally sailing from the air from one island to another at the Tunku Abdul Rahman Marine Park, linking Pulau Gaya and Pulau Sapi.

The zip line enables visitors to cross the narrow straits between both islands in about 30 to 40 seconds.

The starting point of the line begins from the top of a hill at Pulau Gaya, (about 45m above sea level) and riders gradually descend to a 8m-high platform at Pulau Sapi.

The zip line operates between 10am and 4pm daily. 
Operator: http://bit.ly/1w8ZeOp
Video Link: http://bit.ly/VRXtKq

Tamarind Hill restaurant is one of the first contemporary Thai and Burmese restaurants in the Malaysian dining scene. 
The winner of the industry accolade for Best Asian Cuisine by The Hospitality Asia Platinum Awards for 2003-2004, today Tamarind Hill is set on one of the most spectacular and exclusive private hill top properties in the heart of Kuala Lumpur. 
An introductory menu however extensive, consists of their signature Tom Yam cooked with river lobsters among spicier or subtler soups of sorts, none less Siamese than others yet many are new to local diners. message:
Masak Ikan Tanah Liat, literally translated as fish cooked in clay is a traditional Peninsula Malaysia dish. 
The whole fish is seasoned and wrapped in banana leaves. Wet clay is then packed around this parcel and put into the fire to cook. Locals says the fish will taste sweeter by cooking in this traditional method.

The fishy smell will be absorbed by the clay, making the fish, which is seasoned with onion, chilli, turmeric, lemongrass and shrimp paste taste heavenly.

News Flash:
The Express Rail Link (ERL) from KL Sentral to KLIA2 will commence operations when the KLIA2 airport terminal opens on 2nd May.
Passengers on transit from KLIA can also take ERL’s service, with a one-way inter-terminal transfer between the two terminals priced at RM2 for adults and RM1 for children. The KLIA Ekspres runs on a frequency rate of 15 minutes during peak hours, Mondays to Fridays, and every 20 minutes during off-peak hours and the weekends.

The KLIA Transit runs on a frequency rate of 20 minutes during peak hours, Mondays to Fridays, and every 30 minutes during off-peak hours and the weekends.

message:
Eurasian cuisine refers to dishes created from the influence of inter-marriage between the Europeans and the locals. 
In Malaysia, the unique cuisine has evolved from a blend of Portuguese colonization of Melaka in the early 16th Century, and later the Dutch and British rule. These dishes may have Portuguese origins as well as absorbed local ingredients like chillies, sambal belacan and pickles (acar). Some were even inspired by British and Indian food.

Whatever it is, one thing is certain – Eurasian dishes are not as widely available as other communities but the cuisines are kept alive by individuals.

message: Good Morning Peeps, have a wonderful week ahead. :)

Angling or fishing is a thrilling activity in Malaysia. The variety of freshwater and marine environments offers fantastic angling opportunities. Whether it is for serious game fishing or fun, Malaysia boasts a plethora of angling destinations.

Malaysia’s wide range of rivers and natural and artificial lakes are home for over 300 species of freshwater fish, and among them, around 40 species can be caught on rod and line. Some prime freshwater sport fishes include the Giant Snakehead, Malaysian Jungle Perch, the Giant Featherback, freshwater Catfish and Malaysian Mahseer. 

Freshwater fishing can be relatively easy with many pay ponds located near to many towns in the West Coast. For more serious anglers, jungle excursions combined with jungle trekking and camping can also be arranged through angling operators throughout the country. On top of rivers and lakes, angling on deep waters can be found on the Spratlys, off the coast of Sabah is Malaysia’s premier saltwater game fishing destination. The islands offshore from Rompin, Johor, are playgrounds of the Pacific Sailfish. Other deepwater fishes are Black Marlins, Blue Marlins, Striped Marlins and Tuna (Yellowfin, Bigeye and Dogtooth).

What about from LCCT.
Bukhairy Khairy Rasid, nur Nur Hafizh, Syazwan Osman. Zaini Mohd Salleh. M Samat Kahat.

I have been to Malaysia countless times. And I have taken these metered cabs from KLIA before. I'm sorry to say this but unless you are savvy with Malaysia roads and can speak Malay, chances of you getting ripped off even with a metered taxi is still there. He might just take you through roads which will probably end up with you coughing up almost the same amount as taking the premium ones. So, now I drive to KL or take the airport coach. No matter what system is in place, please be careful. Just sharing my past bad experience with those who might not be aware. :-)

message:
Hi Peeps... we heard David and Victoria Beckham will be in Istana Budaya, Kuala Lumpur on 26 March for the World’s premier honours event in the sporting calendar, Laureus World Sports Awards. *excited*

The globally televised Awards Ceremony, attended by living legends of sport, celebrates the achievements of the greatest sportsmen and sportswomen each year. Among the sporting greats who have been named as winners of Awards over the 15 years of Laureus have been Usain Bolt, Lindsay Vonn, Roger Federer, Serena Williams and Rafael Nadal. 

Malaysia is honoured to have been given the privilege of hosting the prestigious 2014 Awards and Kuala Lumpur looks forward to staging this internationally-renowned event and welcoming a plethora of sporting legends.

message:
Lonely Planet has listed Penang as the Number One Culinary Hotspot in the world for 2014. 

Lonely Planet’s commissioning editor, Robin Barton wrote of Penang: “Malaysian hawker food has spread worldwide through food trucks and pop-ups but nothing compares to Penang. Its food reflects the intermingling of the many cultures that arrived after Penang was set up as a trading port in 1786, from Malays to Indians, Achenese to Chinese, Burmese to Thais. The state capital, George Town is its culinary epicenter.”

We are certain you would agree with him. :)

If you are heading to Singapore Expo at NATAS Fair 2014 on 28 Feb - 2 Mar, come by Tourism Malaysia - Singapore's booth (3H47) to taste the authentic Penang Rojak.

message:
One of Penang’s best kept herbal beauty secret, pegaga in Bahasa Malaysia (commonly known as centella asiatice in English) is a member of the parsley family and grows wild alongside ordinary grass. Pegaga leaves possess several qualities that cause a chain of beneficial effects in the body.

The Malay community are fond of pegaga, which is either served raw, mixed with coconut and crushed fresh chillies as kerabu (salad) or eaten with sambal belacan. 
Penangites even blend it to make it as a juice.

Do try it when you are in Penang.

message:
Travelling to Malacca this weekend?
We recommend that you try this much sought-after dish.

Asam Pedas, which translates as ‘sour and spicy’ is a traditional Malay dish which Malacca is known for, consisting of a choice of fish or beef served in a hot and sour soup.
A great place to sample this local speciality, which has the unique characteristic of both cooking and serving their asam pedas in a clay pot dish that ensures your food stays hot.
Renowned for its recipe and offers a selection of beef & fish, including red snapper, tenggiri and also stingray, this restaurant is popular among locals.

A must for anyone wishing to experience real local food in Malacca.


Kota Laksamana 1 Asam Pedas Claypot Restaurant
86 Laksaman 5, Taman Kota Laksamana, Melaka 75200.
Open Daily: 17.00 Hrs – 05.00Hrs
GPS Coordinates: 2.195946,102.244374 

#vmy2014 #tmsingapore

message:
Dosa for breakfast, anyone?

Sometimes spelled as "thosai", dosa is a South Indian dish thought to be over 900 years old. A thin crepe made from pounded rice and lentils is fried golden-brown on one side only, then folded around meat or vegetables. Dosa is a good Malaysian Indian food choice for people with wheat allergies.

'Apam Balik' is Malaysia's traditional pancake, usually sold at specialist roadside stalls throughout Malaysia. It gets its name from the way it is folded over when taken out from the special brass pan when it is cooked. 

The traditional Apam Balik is filled with ground peanuts, sugar and sweet corn. It is a favourite Malaysian street food and makes a delicious snack.

*Known also as Ban Jian Kuih, Chin Loong Pau, Martabak Manis, Terang Bulan, Apam Pulau Pinang or Kuih Haji in certain areas of Malaysia.

Pasar Malam (literally means 'Night Market or Night Bazaar' in the Malay Language) brings together a collection of stalls that sells items at cheap prices. 

Have you been to the longest pasar malam in Malaysia?
Setia Alam Pasar Malam is officially the longest Pasar Malam in Malaysia, as confirmed by the Malaysia Book of Records. It stretches over 2.4KM with more than 600 stalls. It is hailed as the food paradise in Setia Alam which consists of both local and international delights.

Setia Alam Night Market is open every Saturday from 6pm-11pm.

message:
Sekinchan is a small, cozy farming and fishing village just north of Kuala Lumpur. It has gotten extremely popular over the years with city slickers heading over to enjoy the simpler things in life.

The drive to Sekinchan is scenic with oil palm trees along the coastal road, stalls selling handmade cotton pillows, eateries offering a wide variety of local delicacies and almost in the middle of nowhere, vast expanses of paddy fields bordering a stretch of fishing villages.

The picturesque landscape in Sekinchan especially when the sun sets against the vast padi fields and stretch of fishing villages is the one of the many reasons why visitors call this town 'a photographer’s haven'.

A MUST-VISIT for photographers.  :)

GPS Location : N03 30.984 E101 06.891

description:
ASEAN Tourism Forum (ATF) is a cooperative regional effort to promote the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) region as one tourist destination where Asian hospitality and cultural diversity are at its best. This annual event involves all the tourism industry sectors of the 10 member nations of ASEAN: Brunei Darussalam, Cambodia, Indonesia, Lao PDR, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.

Each year, the hosting of ATF is rotated among the member countries. ATF 2014 marks the 33rd anniversary of this event since its inauguration in Malaysia in 1981. The country and its host city Kuching, Sarawak is all geared up to welcome over 1,600 delegates which includes some 150 ASEAN tourism ministers and officials, 500 ASEAN exhibitors, 500 international buyers, 100 international and local media as well as 100 tourism trade visitors.

message:
Its the season of Dabai. What is Dabai, you may ask?  :)

It is a native fruit of Sarawak harvested by local natives and sold it in the native market. The fruit is also called 'Sibu olive', 'black olive' or 'tropical olive'.

The dabai is a large tree growing up to 20m high. it is a course tree with a tall straight trunk, big stems and branches, and large compound leaves. Being dioeciously, there are male and female trees. 

Want to try? Only available in Sarawak...  :)

data.message: hi, was lucky enough to see raflesia in full bloom last month in Sabah!

message:
Have you seen a Rafflesia?

Rare, beautifully exotic, the Rafflesia flower is a real treat for those lucky enough to see it when travelling in Borneo. The world's heaviest flower blooms for only three to five days, unexpectedly any time of year, before turning black with decay. 
Smells like rotting meat near the end of its life cycle, it attract flies and other insects for reproduction. The rafflesia is one of the world's rarest flowers for good reason: nearly perfect conditions must exist for the flower to bloom. 

Did you know?
Rafflesia flower sometimes blooms in the Cameron Highlands, Pahang.
name: Timeline Photos

message:
Planning a romantic getaway and still want Penang authentic dishes?

Seven Terraces is a newly opened small private hotel of only 18 suites. The owners converted a grand row of seven C19th Anglo Chinese terraces, in one of Penang’s finest and most intact heritage streets, into a romantic, beautiful and timeless retreat, perfectly positioned in the very heart of the World Heritage Site and just a few minutes walk from all the major icons. 
It successfully captures and celebrates the spirit of this world heritage town and its unique peranakan culture.

For more info, contact info@seventerraces.com

66 Porsche cars of various models made its way from Singapore to Malaysia, with Putrajaya as the first stop, joined by 60 other members from the Malaysia Porsche Club. Thereafter, they headed off to The Chateau Spa and Organic Wellness Resort at Berjaya Hills in Bukit Tinggi. 

Malaysia welcomes more motor clubs to organise such trips.  :)

message:
Have you been to the Mini Malaysia & Asean Cultural Park?
It is located a few kilometres outside of Melaka, near the town of Ayer Keroh. If traditional architecture interest you, this is a great place to explore. Each of the houses represents the architectural style of the 13 states in Malaysia and is furnished with various items, arts and crafts which depict the culture of each state. 
Other attractions in the park includes weekly cultural shows and traditional games.

Do explore when you are visiting Melaka on your next trip.
name: Places of interest
story: Tourism Malaysia at Mini Malaysia & Asean Cultural Park.

The highest mountain in the Malay Archipelago, Mount Kinabalu and its surroundings are among the most important biological sites in the world, with between 5000 and 6000 species of plants, 326 species of birds, and more than 100 mammalian species identified. 
Among this rich collection of wildlife are famous species such as the gigantic Rafflesia plants and the orang-utan.

data.message:
Rent a motorbike at Pangkor if you can, so you can zip across the island with ease plus it's more fun. if you can't ride, then bring someone who can :p 

Lots of fun water sport activities to try, including snorkeling. Beaches are natural, clean and beautiful.
Lovely Pangkor with its pretty beaches, yummy seafood and wonderful kampong vibes!

Perak has a lot to offer I used to live in Ipoh, the food always great. But the best place is travelling from Kuala Kangsar towards Jeli-Kelantan. I fell in love with The Royal Belum Forest n Temenggor Lake n the Jungle of Perak.

My family and I went to Belum Rainforest and Lake Temenggor in June 2001.  We had an awesome trip - exploring the lower part of Belum where we trekked up the slippery ground in search of the famous rafflesia, an eye-opening visit to the  aborigines village where life is very simple and basic and time seems to stand still, and a tiring but rewarding trek up to Sungai Enam Base Camp where we had a refreshing dip in the cool waterfall. 

We were there for 5 days, exploring the Banding trail, belum rainforest, the nearby town of Gerik (we had lovely chats with the friendly locals and I got to try the ikan pekasam which I like so much) and even managed a day trip to Betong, Thailand through the Pengkalan Hulu border. I must say that our trip to Belum was very exciting and adventurous for us. We even enjoyed the long road trip (we drove abt 10 hrs all the way from S'pore to Banding), taking in the lovely sights of the natural landscape that 'paints' the state of Perak.

The 40,000-hectare Matang Mangrove Forest in Kuala Sepetang. Today, it is recognized as the best managed sustainable mangrove ecosystem in the world. Lots of interesting activities can be done, such as strolling on wooden boardwalk, replanting of saplings, studying numerous ways of fishing, bird watching, and much more!

Had a blast of a time wid my family at Pangkor last June.Although a bit quiet, we had the pool at Anjungan Resort almost to ourselves.Saw lots of  the famous hornbills of Pangkor n done our dried seafood shopping galore.We love the tranquillity n peace of the island :-)

I just came back from Jalan Bukit Merah Laketown Resort at Perak with my family. My three children of age 9, 7 and 6 love the place very much. The resort have everything, Eco  park, water park and cable lift rides. Best of all there is a orangutan sanctuary with the near extinct Borneo species. Food and accommodation are great too.

message: A very good morning to all FBians. Who's looking forward to the festive weekend? Show us some 'likes'... 😊

Morning FBians, are there any BASE Jumpers among you or do you know of anyone who does BASE Jump?

What is BASE Jump?
It is an extreme sports in which a person parachutes from a fixed object. B.A.S.E stands for Building, Antennas, Spans (bridges) and Earth (cliffs).

How to participate?
Experience requirements:
- Be considered once they have completed a 120 BASE jumps.  
- Have made at least 20 BASE jumps within the previous 12 months. 
- Preferably have been actively BASE jumping for at least 2 years.

*Sets by Base Jumping Organizer. Gary Cunningham, President of Australian BASE Association.

TaxiMonger brings Johor Bahru’s first taxi booking service through smartphones for trips to Malaysia. Passengers can book for metered taxis whether on adhoc basis or in advance. Exclusively partnered with JB-Tek Bhd to connect passengers in Singapore with the taxi-drivers of JB-Tek Bhd for a service app called as ‘Trip To Malaysia’.
Passengers from Singapore would now be able to go to any of the tourists’ destinations, points of interests and key cities in Malaysia through JB-Tek’s assigned Executive Taxis. The selected destinations offered by TaxiMonger range from as near as Johor Bahru and going as far as Pulau Langkawi. 

For more information, log on to www.taximonger.com

Great mountain, white beaches, different tribes are just the many reasons for East Malaysia.  A great close destination, our neighbour, Malaysia Truly Asia.....

Malaysia offers one of the most ideal destination for travel. Malaysia offers a varied range of activities from the highlands of Cameron Highlands and the lush greenery of the oldest rainforest to the white sandy beaches. There is always that city limelights that beckons you for a night out of fun or self indulgence. The ethnic diversity is shared in the myriad colours in traditional wear, the culinary delight that is shared by all and the warmth welcoming hospitality greeted you as you travel around Malaysia . From the Portugese settlers in Melaka to the unique Baba culture to the 3 main ethnic group, there is always an experience and a sweet memory to savior.
Truly Malaysia with lots of friendly faces, nice local delights and free from war. Malaysia has lots of facinating places which could reduce our stress life in Singapore

I love to travel to KL and its outskirts.   It offers both new modern shopping centres of mega scales like One Utama or Midvalley to Hypermarkets like Tesco to wholesale like Kenaga etc and yet you can find diversity in old shops in many areas to pasar malam in different vicinity and the open markets like in Jalan Ara.  Simply love the mood when I can go slow or at a fast pace,  the crowd yet you don't find it claustrophobic , the buzz and lively atmosphere you may find at Pavillion dining boulevard close to midnight and above all I felt relaxed each time I am there.  

The main draw for me is the food scene and you are spoilt for choices.  Each time I am there I never fail to make new discoveries and I am so often thrilled by the gem of the new found place and the smacking good food it offers.  

I indulged in the many nice hotels that abounds in KL and I am a frequent customer of Prince Hotel, my favorite accommodation in KL for its image, service, accessibility and proximity to the shopping belts and a short walk away from the midnight movie that I catch at the Pavillion.   

Taxis have been my favorite mode of transportation, so easily available and I always got a wealth of information on places to drink and dine and places of interest.

Truly it's a haven for tourist like me!
Warm Malaysian Hospitality,authentic local delights,culture and traditions,homestay,indulge in various village pastimes,agro visits delights of rural living

I love foremost the exotic beaches at Redang, green lushful mountains in Kedah the hilly stations. Shopping in KLCC is awesome and can never be enough. Foods are finger licking and many Halal certified restaurant. Last but not least, Malaysians are friendly by nature and approachable.

1st & foremost love to go holiday to Malaysia because of the foods that really appeal to my appetite. Stay in their exclusive 5 star hotel & visit their interesting attractions place that sure brings me & family to go holiday to Malaysia. We plan to go holiday to Kelantan to visit my long penpal when I get to know her I was in my teens.

From the crystal blue waters around the famed island of Sipadan, where divers are surrounded by turtles, schools of jacks and the chance to dive around the only island that is not connected to any continent. To the idyllic island of Langkawi where one can relax under a beach umbrella at Pantai Cenang idling away your time.

Stopping over in Malacca for the foodie lover and moving on to Kuala Lumpur to indulge more in local food and shopping. To burn away all that excess calories, why not opt being 'Tarzan or Jane' for a day and traverse between tree to tree at SkyTrek Adventure Park? If climbing is not your cup of tea, perhaps exploring Mulu caves in Sarawak may bring you back to nature. 

For the adrenaline junkie, Sepang tracks await you and if you do not have a car to speed your way through the tracks, how about Go-karting instead?

So with that many options available and many more places to explore just a doorstep away, how can Malaysia not attract me over?

Malaysis is the one of the most pleasant, hassle-free countries to visit in 
S.E.A. Its buoyant and wealthy culture based on a vibrant fusion of Malay, Chinese and Indian .
Malaysia has a wide range of tourist attraction. This include the hi-tech city Kuala Lumpur to the tropical island if Langkawi. Malaysia has the potential of catering to tourist of every hue and truly lives up to its tag line of Malaysia truly Asia.

The diversity of the unique cultural traditions, the well-deserved reputation of food heaven in South East Asia and the friendliness of the people there are simply so welcoming.  It is like a home away from home. A perfect place for a getaway, to rest and to relax. For this, i am truly in love with Malaysia.

Have u seen Rafflesia in Sabah ? its so attractive and cannot move your eyes aways from it. i saw six.

A non-Halal dish, Tuaran mee is a famous hawker dish of Sabah.
Made of egg yolk batter and flour, which gives the noodle a yummy egg aroma when fried. It is usually cooked with local vegetables,various meats or seafood, and eggs. 
This dish was made popular in Tuaran (a town as well as a district located in the northwest of Sabah), hence the name.

Seri Chenang Resort & Spa Langkawi is a luxury boutique resort consisting of 6 villas of different sizes and unique characteristics, built to replicate Malay traditional houses representing several states in Malaysia of regal stature housing 10 different types of accommodation. 
Perched on the banks of Kuala Chenang River next to the popular Chenang Beach, the resort is set in lush tropical foliage with sweeping views of the paddy fields, mountains and the sea, nestled within the more quiet and exclusive fishermen village of Kampung Sungai Kuala Chenang. 
The resort is also complemented by facilities such as an infinity swimming pool, a small gymnasium, an art gallery, a resort boutique and most importantly, the exclusively designed Kayangan Spa.

message:
Johor State has three wetlands of international importance. They are Tanjung Piai, Kukup Island and Sungai Pulai. They has received international recognition, being granted the status of a 'Wetland of International Importance' (RAMSAR site) by the Geneva- based Ramsar Convention Bureau. 

Located 90km south of Johor Bahru's city centre, Tanjung Piai's natural wonders have been gazetted into a National Park. Its beautiful mangroves, important for their resilience, are one of the mainstays to sustainable growth of the various mangrove wildlife. They also serve to protect the land from the fierce onslaught of the wild sea.

Kukup Island is one of the largest uninhabited mangroves in the world. It is also the only one situated in Johor waters. 
Kukup is today the home of countless species of wildlife. Among these are playful monkeys, quiet mudskippers and nosy wild boars.

Sungai Pulai is the largest riverine mangrove system in the state of Johor, located at the estuary of the Sungai Pulai river. With its associated sea grass beds, intertidal mudflats and inland freshwater riverine forest, the site represents one of the best examples of a lowland tropical river basin, supporting a rich biodiversity dependent on mangrove.

message:
Our colleague, Nadzri headed for a recce road trip to Lemako Falls last week. Lemako Falls is located in Labis Permanent Forest Reserve, Johor. A permit is required and can be obtain from the Forestry Johor State Department.
To get there using the North South Expressway, exit at Ayer Hitam and head to Kluang town. Drive towards the small town of Kahang. To get into the waterfall area, a 4 wheel drive vehicle is required due to rugged terrain and log road.
It takes about 42 kilometres from the main road and about 3 hours of slow driving to the Falls.


Link: http://www.forestry.gov.my/johor/index.php?lang=en

message:
Set in a craggy, almost magical setting of limestone outcroppings rising sharply out of the calm Andaman Sea, the mangrove forest in Langkawi is really an intricate network of streams and hidden coves that are home to hundreds of endemic jungle species of wildlife.
The highlight of any tour to the mangroves is the feeding of the eagles. Your boatman will throw food into the water near your boat and wait for these huge birds to circle overhead and swoop in for their 'lunch'.

message:
Good Sunday FBians.
'Like' this if you wish to try Kelantan's popular breakfast dish...

Nasi Dagang is a Malaysian dish consisting of a mix of white and brown glutinous rice cooked with coconut milk, fish curry and extra ingredients such as fried shaved coconut, hard-boiled eggs and vegetable pickles. Nasi Dagang literally means “Trading Rice”.
It is a well-known breakfast food in the states on the East Coast of Peninsular Malaysia, such as Terengganu and Kelantan.

Join us at Raffles City Convention Centre, Singapore on 5th March (Tuesday) to get a taste of Kelantan's cuisine. Simply RSVP with us through FB message.

message:
JOHOR ISLANDS: 
Tengah Island (widely known as Pulau Tengah)

Tengah Island lies nine nautical miles off the coast of Mersing on the South China Sea, off the east coast of Johor. This uninhabited island is about 3 hours away from Singapore (2 hours drive to Mersing and thereafter, a 45 minutes boat ride to the island) and a great place to watch the giant leatherback turtles come ashore to lay eggs yearly, especially so during the month of July.

Batu Batu is a private island boutique resort built in the Malay vernacular architecture, consisting of 20 one bedroom and 2 two bedroom villas. For more information, do visit their resort link below:

Link: www.batubatu.com.my

HOLIDAY ANNOUNCEMENT: Tourism Malaysia - Singapore office will be closed this Friday (01Feb) and will resume operations on Monday (04Feb). This is due to Federal Territory Day,a state holiday in Malaysia.
The date marks the anniversary of the formation of Kuala Lumpur, which took place in 1974. Ten years later, Labuan became the second federal territory and Putrajaya became the third federal territory of Malaysia in 2001.

NON-HALAL dish: Bak Kut Teh (Meat Bone Tea)

We found many Singaporeans will always include this dish in their itinerary whenever they visit Malaysia.   
If you didn't already know, Klang Town is famous for this breakfast dish. You can find it almost at every street corner. If you haven't tried it, do give it a go in your next visit.  ( ＾◡＾)

caption: Penang Thaipusam Celebration
description: Penang Thaipusam Celebration takes place on 26th to 28th January. This annual festival, which marks the full moon of the Tamil month of Thai, is observed by the Hindu community. During this auspicious day, worshippers would gather at the temple to give their prayers and offerings to their deity. This year's festivity will be held in the Waterfall Hilltop temple, also known as Arulmigu Balathandayuthapani temple. It is also the final point of their kavadi procession. Not to be missed are sightings of the chariot procession on Jan 26 and the impressive kavadi bearers on Jan 27, who are part of a religious worship in dedication to deity Murugan.

NEWS RELEASE: 
Tourists visiting Malaysia can now enjoy further discounts when shopping at participating malls within the Bukit Bintang KLCC (BBKLCC) shopping district during the 1Malaysia Mega Sale Carnival from 15 June to 2 September 2012 and the 1Malaysia Year End Sale from 15 November 2012 to 2 January 2013. With a host of nine shopping centres within walking distance of one to another, BBKLCC offers 3000 stores, a variety of shopping, dining and urban leisure experiences. Tourists simply need to approach the information counters/concierge desks of participating malls and present their passports as verification of identity.A card will be activated and given on the spot, which is valid for one week.

Shop, Eat and Celebrate! The 1Malaysia Mega Sale Carnival 2012 is set to woo shoppers with a string of promotions and tempting discounts for 7 whole weeks. 

Kicking off on 15 June till 2 Sept, the sale carnival brings you even more bargains with the onset of the Hari Raya Puasa festivities and the 1Malaysia Unified Sale which runs concurrently, to offer you more than just retail goods. So look within and beyond shopping malls and experience a wholesome shopping spree.

Be prepared for one of the biggest sales event in the country, the 1Malaysia Mega Sale Carnival.

data.message: Hi guys. Just a feedback. My family and I have been wanting to explore Trengganu and its beautiful islands for quite some time now. But honestly, we have shelved the idea as there is no direct flight to Kuala Trengganu from either Changi Airport or Senai. At present the flight to Trengganu via KLIA is a no brainer as its involves a stop-over and price-wise, fyi, it is cheaper for us to fly to Koh Samui or Phuket. On the other hand, we will not travel by bus as the journey is impossibly long for our kids. So while we want to support tourism in Malaysia, I think its about time for MAS, Firefly or Airasia do the right thing! I am hoping for a positive response as I do want to see more success in the tourism sector in East Malaysia which has lots of potential and is indeed an untapped market at present. Thanking you in advance.

Dear Naharudin Shariff, thank you for your feedback. As we would always encourage airlines to support,it is entirely up to their discretion on whether to travel to any routes. This is because, as we understand it,they would need to consider many factors,examples like passenger travel loads and revenue.

message:
The March school holidays is near. 
Give your child the experience of "working life" by role-playing at up to 90 real-life jobs. 
Children can choose to be a judge, banker, journalist, painter, actor, magician or other professions through the role-playing activities at the newly opened Kidzania Kuala Lumpur.With a boarding pass, a map and a cheque for 50 kidZos (Kidzania's currency), a child can choose an occupation, learn about the job, wear the uniform and experience a simulation of real-life work environment.Some of the activities include putting out fires, being a surgeon for a day, piloting an aeroplane, hosting a television programme or interior designing.
How COOL is that? 
Don't you wish you had similar real life role-playing activities when you were young?  :)

Kidzania is located at Curve NX in Mutiara Damansara. It operates in two shifts during the school holidays from 10am to 3pm and 4pm to 9pm.

message:
North Borneo Train is back on Track!!!!

The North Borneo Railway’s rich history starts way back in the 1880′s when the North Borneo Charted Company, the administrators of Sabah, then called North Borneo, mooted the idea of a railway for the first time.

The North Borneo Railway was temporarily closed in September 2005 due to the upgrading works of the railway track by the Ministry of Transportation. The North Borneo Railway continued its service on 4th July 2011 after the upgrading works was completed

大马果中之王－榴莲盛产大丰收，喜欢榴莲的朋友可乘这两个月榴莲季节，大吃特吃！榴莲的魅力无法挡，连新加坡的“榴莲发烧友”也纷纷组队前往永平和昔加末境内的榴莲园吃榴莲。

大马旅游局配合榴莲季节，在柔佛州的昔加末举办“榴莲节”（Pesta Durian），现场尽是榴莲香！Pesta Durian从昨天开始在昔加末广场（Dataran Segamat）举行，并将于今天傍晚结束。无法到场的朋友，可在这两个月内结伴到昔加末、永平和Tangkak寻榴莲！今年，由于柔佛州和彭亨州的榴莲同时盛产，榴莲价格比以往便宜，还等什么？

From 15 June 2011 onwards, Melaka will become smoke-free zones, making it the first state in the country to gazette specific areas where smoking is banned.

The areas comprise the entire 4.2 square kilometres of World Heritage City of Melaka, Melaka Raya (commercial centre), Melaka International Trade Centre (MITC) at Ayer Keroh and the Alor Gajah and Jasin town centres.

Those who are caught smoking at the designated smoke-free areas could face fines starting at RM300 although the maximum compound is RM5,000.

caption:
Johor, the southernmost state of the peninsular, is steeped in history and is a haven for nature lovers. The state has an unbroken coastline flanked by the South China Sea in the east, extending around its southern tip to the western shoreline overlooking the straits of Malacca.
The magical islands of Johor are endowed with crystal clear waters, powdery white sand and colourful marine life.

message:
GEORGE TOWN: The new Swiss-made coaches for the Penang Hill funicular train service have arrived.

The two new air-conditioned coaches, which can carry 50 people each, will travel non-stop between the foot of the hill and the top station under the upgraded system unlike the old system where passengers have to change trains at the middle station.

The commuting time of the new service would be less than 10 minutes per way compared to 30 minutes previously. It would be able to carry 1,000 passengers per hour compared to 250 under the old system. The coaches would be able to glide down at a slower speed to the lower station should there be any technical glitch or power supply disruption and there would also be a sensor system to enable early detection of landslides or trees falling onto the rail tracks as well as a stand-by generator to provide power should there be electricity supply disruption.
name: Timeline Photos

message:
PULAU PERHENTIAN – TOP 10 BEACH TO SWING A HAMMOCK – 
SAYS LONELY PLANET

Pulau Perhentian is one of the world’s most “idyllic, sun-kissed refuges,” 
according to Lonely Planet, the world’s largest travel guide firm

Sapphire blue waters, white sandy beaches, jungle trekking, diving, and an all time favourite—sun bathing—these are just a few things to be found and experienced at Pulau Perhentian in Malaysia. Lonely Planet ranked this beautiful beach as the fifth “Best Beach to Swing a Hammock” in its 1000 Ultimate Experiences for 2010.

Pulau Perhentian, meaning 'stopover island,' consists of two islands: Pulau Perhentian Besar and Pulau Perhentian Kecil. 

It is located just off the edge of the Pulau Redang Marine Park, Perhentian's coral-fringed waters have excellent underwater seascapes for snorkeling and scuba diving. Arrangements can also be made for island cruises, and boats can be hired to explore private bays and secluded coves.
